        -:   58:/** \class Matrix
        -:   59:  * \ingroup Core_Module
        -:   60:  *
        -:   61:  * \brief The matrix class, also used for vectors and row-vectors
        -:   62:  *
        -:   63:  * The %Matrix class is the work-horse for all \em dense (\ref dense "note") matrices and vectors within Eigen.
        -:   64:  * Vectors are matrices with one column, and row-vectors are matrices with one row.
        -:   65:  *
        -:   66:  * The %Matrix class encompasses \em both fixed-size and dynamic-size objects (\ref fixedsize "note").
        -:   67:  *
        -:   68:  * The first three template parameters are required:
        -:   69:  * \tparam Scalar_ Numeric type, e.g. float, double, int or std::complex<float>.
        -:   70:  *                 User defined scalar types are supported as well (see \ref user_defined_scalars "here").
        -:   71:  * \tparam Rows_ Number of rows, or \b Dynamic
        -:   72:  * \tparam Cols_ Number of columns, or \b Dynamic
        -:   73:  *
        -:   74:  * The remaining template parameters are optional -- in most cases you don't have to worry about them.
        -:   75:  * \tparam Options_ A combination of either \b #RowMajor or \b #ColMajor, and of either
        -:   76:  *                 \b #AutoAlign or \b #DontAlign.
        -:   77:  *                 The former controls \ref TopicStorageOrders "storage order", and defaults to column-major. The latter controls alignment, which is required
        -:   78:  *                 for vectorization. It defaults to aligning matrices except for fixed sizes that aren't a multiple of the packet size.
        -:   79:  * \tparam MaxRows_ Maximum number of rows. Defaults to \a Rows_ (\ref maxrows "note").
        -:   80:  * \tparam MaxCols_ Maximum number of columns. Defaults to \a Cols_ (\ref maxrows "note").
        -:   81:  *
        -:   82:  * Eigen provides a number of typedefs covering the usual cases. Here are some examples:
        -:   83:  *
        -:   84:  * \li \c Matrix2d is a 2x2 square matrix of doubles (\c Matrix<double, 2, 2>)
        -:   85:  * \li \c Vector4f is a vector of 4 floats (\c Matrix<float, 4, 1>)
        -:   86:  * \li \c RowVector3i is a row-vector of 3 ints (\c Matrix<int, 1, 3>)
        -:   87:  *
        -:   88:  * \li \c MatrixXf is a dynamic-size matrix of floats (\c Matrix<float, Dynamic, Dynamic>)
        -:   89:  * \li \c VectorXf is a dynamic-size vector of floats (\c Matrix<float, Dynamic, 1>)
        -:   90:  *
        -:   91:  * \li \c Matrix2Xf is a partially fixed-size (dynamic-size) matrix of floats (\c Matrix<float, 2, Dynamic>)
        -:   92:  * \li \c MatrixX3d is a partially dynamic-size (fixed-size) matrix of double (\c Matrix<double, Dynamic, 3>)
        -:   93:  *
        -:   94:  * See \link matrixtypedefs this page \endlink for a complete list of predefined \em %Matrix and \em Vector typedefs.
        -:   95:  *
        -:   96:  * You can access elements of vectors and matrices using normal subscripting:
        -:   97:  *
        -:   98:  * \code
        -:   99:  * Eigen::VectorXd v(10);
        -:  100:  * v[0] = 0.1;
        -:  101:  * v[1] = 0.2;
        -:  102:  * v(0) = 0.3;
        -:  103:  * v(1) = 0.4;
        -:  104:  *
        -:  105:  * Eigen::MatrixXi m(10, 10);
        -:  106:  * m(0, 1) = 1;
        -:  107:  * m(0, 2) = 2;
        -:  108:  * m(0, 3) = 3;
        -:  109:  * \endcode
        -:  110:  *
        -:  111:  * This class can be extended with the help of the plugin mechanism described on the page
        -:  112:  * \ref TopicCustomizing_Plugins by defining the preprocessor symbol \c EIGEN_MATRIX_PLUGIN.
        -:  113:  *
        -:  114:  * <i><b>Some notes:</b></i>
        -:  115:  *
        -:  116:  * <dl>
        -:  117:  * <dt><b>\anchor dense Dense versus sparse:</b></dt>
        -:  118:  * <dd>This %Matrix class handles dense, not sparse matrices and vectors. For sparse matrices and vectors, see the Sparse module.
        -:  119:  *
        -:  120:  * Dense matrices and vectors are plain usual arrays of coefficients. All the coefficients are stored, in an ordinary contiguous array.
        -:  121:  * This is unlike Sparse matrices and vectors where the coefficients are stored as a list of nonzero coefficients.</dd>
        -:  122:  *
        -:  123:  * <dt><b>\anchor fixedsize Fixed-size versus dynamic-size:</b></dt>
        -:  124:  * <dd>Fixed-size means that the numbers of rows and columns are known are compile-time. In this case, Eigen allocates the array
        -:  125:  * of coefficients as a fixed-size array, as a class member. This makes sense for very small matrices, typically up to 4x4, sometimes up
        -:  126:  * to 16x16. Larger matrices should be declared as dynamic-size even if one happens to know their size at compile-time.
        -:  127:  *
        -:  128:  * Dynamic-size means that the numbers of rows or columns are not necessarily known at compile-time. In this case they are runtime
        -:  129:  * variables, and the array of coefficients is allocated dynamically on the heap.
        -:  130:  *
        -:  131:  * Note that \em dense matrices, be they Fixed-size or Dynamic-size, <em>do not</em> expand dynamically in the sense of a std::map.
        -:  132:  * If you want this behavior, see the Sparse module.</dd>
        -:  133:  *
        -:  134:  * <dt><b>\anchor maxrows MaxRows_ and MaxCols_:</b></dt>
        -:  135:  * <dd>In most cases, one just leaves these parameters to the default values.
        -:  136:  * These parameters mean the maximum size of rows and columns that the matrix may have. They are useful in cases
        -:  137:  * when the exact numbers of rows and columns are not known are compile-time, but it is known at compile-time that they cannot
        -:  138:  * exceed a certain value. This happens when taking dynamic-size blocks inside fixed-size matrices: in this case MaxRows_ and MaxCols_
        -:  139:  * are the dimensions of the original matrix, while Rows_ and Cols_ are Dynamic.</dd>
        -:  140:  * </dl>
        -:  141:  *
        -:  142:  * <i><b>ABI and storage layout</b></i>
        -:  143:  *
        -:  144:  * The table below summarizes the ABI of some possible Matrix instances which is fixed thorough the lifetime of Eigen 3.
        -:  145:  * <table  class="manual">
        -:  146:  * <tr><th>Matrix type</th><th>Equivalent C structure</th></tr>
        -:  147:  * <tr><td>\code Matrix<T,Dynamic,Dynamic> \endcode</td><td>\code
        -:  148:  * struct {
        -:  149:  *   T *data;                  // with (size_t(data)%EIGEN_MAX_ALIGN_BYTES)==0
        -:  150:  *   Eigen::Index rows, cols;
        -:  151:  *  };
        -:  152:  * \endcode</td></tr>
        -:  153:  * <tr class="alt"><td>\code
        -:  154:  * Matrix<T,Dynamic,1>
        -:  155:  * Matrix<T,1,Dynamic> \endcode</td><td>\code
        -:  156:  * struct {
        -:  157:  *   T *data;                  // with (size_t(data)%EIGEN_MAX_ALIGN_BYTES)==0
        -:  158:  *   Eigen::Index size;
        -:  159:  *  };
        -:  160:  * \endcode</td></tr>
        -:  161:  * <tr><td>\code Matrix<T,Rows,Cols> \endcode</td><td>\code
        -:  162:  * struct {
        -:  163:  *   T data[Rows*Cols];        // with (size_t(data)%A(Rows*Cols*sizeof(T)))==0
        -:  164:  *  };
        -:  165:  * \endcode</td></tr>
        -:  166:  * <tr class="alt"><td>\code Matrix<T,Dynamic,Dynamic,0,MaxRows,MaxCols> \endcode</td><td>\code
        -:  167:  * struct {
        -:  168:  *   T data[MaxRows*MaxCols];  // with (size_t(data)%A(MaxRows*MaxCols*sizeof(T)))==0
        -:  169:  *   Eigen::Index rows, cols;
        -:  170:  *  };
        -:  171:  * \endcode</td></tr>
        -:  172:  * </table>
        -:  173:  * Note that in this table Rows, Cols, MaxRows and MaxCols are all positive integers. A(S) is defined to the largest possible power-of-two
        -:  174:  * smaller to EIGEN_MAX_STATIC_ALIGN_BYTES.
        -:  175:  *
        -:  176:  * \see MatrixBase for the majority of the API methods for matrices, \ref TopicClassHierarchy,
        -:  177:  * \ref TopicStorageOrders
        -:  178:  */
        -:  179:
        -:  180:template<typename Scalar_, int Rows_, int Cols_, int Options_, int MaxRows_, int MaxCols_>
        -:  181:class Matrix
        -:  182:  : public PlainObjectBase<Matrix<Scalar_, Rows_, Cols_, Options_, MaxRows_, MaxCols_> >
